S.|first1=Alissa J.|last1=Rubin|first2=Ben|last2=Hubbard|date=December 30, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The unilateral U.S. airstrikes were condemned by the Iraqi government, [[Iraqi Armed Forces]] personnel, and Iran, and culminated in the [[Embassy of the United States, Baghdad|U.S. embassy in Baghdad]] being [[Attack on the United States embassy in Baghdad|attacked]] by Iraqi militiamen and their supporters on 31 December 2019. This in turn led to a [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|U.S. airstrike]] near Baghdad International Airport on 3 January 2020, killing Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]] and Iraqi militia commander [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]].\n\n== Background ==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|2019 K-1 Airbase Attack}}\nThe United States [[American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|intervened]] in Iraq in 2014 as a part of [[Operation Inherent Resolve]] (OIR), the U.S.-led mission to degrade and combat the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) terror organization, and have been training and operating alongside Iraqi forces as a part of the anti-ISIL coalition. ISIL was largely beaten back from Iraq in 2017 during the [[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]], with the help of U.S.-backed forces and Sunni and Shia militias. Iran is known to support [[Shia Islam in Iraq|Shia Iraqi]] militias, a number of which are relatively hostile to the U.S. presence in Iraq and the [[Islam in Iraq|Sunni]]-led Iraqi government.<ref name=IranLink/> Tensions rose between [[Iran]] and the U.S. in 2018 when U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] unilaterally pulled out of the [[Iran nuclear deal framework|2015 nuclear deal]] and reimposed sanctions.<ref name=aawsat/>\n\nOn 27 December 2019, the [[K-1 Air Base]] in [[Kirkuk Governorate|Kirkuk province]], Iraq\u2014one of many Iraqi military bases that host Operation Inherent Resolve coalition personnel\u2014was attacked by multiple rockets, killing a U.S. civilian contractor and injuring four U.S. service members and two [[Iraqi security forces]] personnel. The U.S. blamed the Iranian-backed [[Kata'ib Hezbollah]] militia for the attack while the group denied responsibility.<ref name=MaraLago/>\n\nA senior U.S. official said there had been a \"campaign\" of 11 attacks on Iraqi bases hosting OIR personnel in the two months before the 27 December incident, many of which the U.S. attributed to Kata'ib Hezbollah.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/us-airstrikes-iran-tehran-militia-iraq|title=US: strikes on Iran-backed militia a response to 'campaign' of attacks by Tehran|date=30 December 2019|accessdate=1 January 2020|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Military strikes ==\n[[File:DVIDS - Video - US strikes on Kata'ib Hizballah facilities i.webm|thumb|Video of the U.S. strikes on Kata'ib Hezbollah in western Iraq, 29 December 2019]]\nAt around 11:00 am [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]] on 29 December 2019, the United States attacked five [[Kata'ib Hezbollah]] positions in [[Iraq]]i and [[Syria]]n territory. According to the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]], the U.S. targeted three locations in Iraq and two in Syria, including weapon storage facilities and [[command and control]] posts. One U.S. official claimed the strikes were carried out by [[McDonnell Douglas F-15E Strike Eagle|F-15E]] fighter jets using precision-guided bombs and that secondary explosions were observed after some of the strikes, indicating the sites may have contained ammunition. The ammunition facilities held both rockets and drones used by the militia.<ref name=CNN1>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/29/politics/us-strikes-iran-backed-militia-facilities-in-iraq-syria/index.html|title=US strikes 5 facilities in Iraq and Syria linked to Iranian-backed militia|work=CNN|date=29 December 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/29/world/middleeast/us-airstrikes-iran-iraq-syria.html|title=U.S. Launches Airstrikes on Iranian-Backed Forces in Iraq and Syria|work=The New York Times|date=29 December 2019|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ATSD\"/><ref name=MaraLago/>\n\nThe U.S. did not specify the locations of the strikes, but one of the Iraqi strikes had reportedly targeted the militia group's headquarters in or near [[al-Qa'im District]] along the western border with Syria. The strikes in Syria took place along the [[Euphrates]] River Valley in the southeast of the country.<ref name=MaraLago/><ref name=NYT/>\n\n=== Casualties ===\nReportedly, at least 25 militia fighters were killed and 55 wounded.<ref name=aawsat/> According to Iraqi security and militia sources, at least four local Kata'ib Hezbollah commanders were among the dead in the Iraqi strikes, including Abu Ali Khazali.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2019/12/29/Iran-allied-militia-leader-Abu-Ali-Madaniya-among-those-killed-in-US-strike-.html|title=Iran-allied militia leader Abu Ali Khazali among those killed in US strike|website=Al Arabiya|date=29 December 2019}}</ref> U.S. officials could not confirm the militia casualty counts.<ref name=MaraLago/>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n[[File:Secretary of State Pompeo, Secretary of Defense Esper, and Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Gen. Milley Address Reporters (49328112778).jpg|thumb|U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]], Secretary of Defense [[Mark Esper]], and Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Gen. [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]] brief reporters on the airstrikes, 29 December 2019]]\nFollowing the strikes on 29 December, U.S. officials warned that further actions could be undertaken to defend U.S. interests and \"deter further bad behavior from militia groups or from Iran\". U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] was briefed before and after the strikes by his national security advisors and was informed that a further military response could be warranted.<ref name=CNN1/><ref name=MaraLago>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa/trump-aides-call-u-s-strikes-on-iraq-and-syria-successful-warn-of-potential-further-action-idUSKBN1YX0GR|title=Trump aides call U.S. strikes on Iraq and Syria 'successful,' warn of potential further action|date=29 December 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement, U.S. [[Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs|Assistant to the Secretary of Defense]] Jonathan Hoffman called the strikes \"defensive\" and stated that they were in retaliation to prior Kata'ib Hezbollah attacks on both Operation Inherent Resolve coalition forces and their Iraqi partners in prior weeks and months. Hoffman also asserted that the militia has received weapons from Iran's [[Quds Force]] that have been used to attack OIR forces.<ref name=ATSD/> U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] considered the attacks a warning against any actions by Iran that endangers the lives of Americans.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.france24.com/en/20191229-us-bombs-militant-group-in-iraq-syria-in-retaliation-for-contractor-s-killing |title= US bombs pro-Iran militant group in Iraq, Syria in retaliation for rocket attack. |}}</ref>\n\n=== Reactions in Iraq ===\nAn [[Iraqi Armed Forces]] spokesman stated that U.S. Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]] informed Iraqi Prime Minister [[Adil Abdul-Mahdi]] half an hour before the operation, to which he strongly objected to and condemned; the spokesman called the unilateral U.S. airstrikes \"a treacherous stab in the back\".<ref name=CNN1/> Prime Minister Abdul-Mahdi later declared three [[day of national mourning|days of national mourning]], from 31 December 2019 until 2 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.masrawy.com/news/news_publicaffairs/details/2019/12/31/1697719/\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062f-\u0631\u0633\u0645\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642-\u0639\u0644\u0649-\u0636\u062d\u0627\u064a\u0627-\u0627\u0644\u063a\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a-\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0629|title=\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0631\u0633\u0645\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0636\u062d\u0627\u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0629|website=\u0645\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0648\u064a.\u0643\u0648\u0645|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref><ref name=aawsat/> The Prime Minister also argued that the attack did not take place based on evidence, but rather on situations caused by the tensions between Iran and the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/news/politics/2019/12/31/\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642-\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0634\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628\u064a-\u0627\u062d\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062c\u0627\u062a-\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a-\u0627\u0644\u0648\u0644\u0627\u064a\u0627\u062a-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629|title=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642.. \u0627\u062d\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0636\u062f \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0641 \"\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0634\u062f\" \u0648\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u064a\u0647\u062f\u062f \u0628\u0645\u0631\u0627\u062c\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0629 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0644\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u064a|website=www.aljazeera.net|language=ar|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\nSenior [[Popular Mobilization Forces|Popular Mobilization Units]] commander Jamal Jaafar Ibrahimi said \"Our response will be very tough on the American forces in Iraq\".<ref name=aawsat/> \n\n==== U.S. embassy attack ====\n{{Main|Attack on the United States embassy in Baghdad}}\nOn 31 December, PMU militiamen and their supporters attacked the [[Embassy of the United States, Baghdad|U.S. Embassy in Baghdad]], prompting the U.S. to deploy additional soldiers to help quell the situation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iraq-us-embassy-shooting-baghdad-iran-airstrikes-protest-a9265221.html|title=Iraqi protesters break down gate and storm US embassy as gunshots ring out|date=December 31, 2019|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/75228a8a607a44863b57021ac33264dc|title=Militiamen breach US Embassy in Baghdad; Trump blames Iran|date=December 31, 2019|website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\n=== Other reactions ===\n* {{flag|Iran}} - Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman [[Abbas Mousavi]] said that the U.S. has \"openly shown its support to terrorism and shown its negligence to the independence and national sovereignty of countries\". He added that the U.S. must accept responsibility of the consequences of the \"illegal attacks\".<ref name=CNN2>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/30/middleeast/iraq-us-airstrikes-reaction-intl/index.html|title=Iran warns of 'consequences' after US strikes in Iraq and Syria|date=30 December 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019|work=CNN}}</ref> In response to U.S. assertions that Iran was behind the Iraqi airbase attacks, the supreme leader of Iran [[Twitter|tweeted]] \"If Iran wants to fight a country, it will strike directly.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Khamenei_fa/status/1212299106321870848|title=\u0645\u06cc\u0628\u06cc\u0646\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0647\u06cc\u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0636\u062f\u0622\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u06a9\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0686\u0642\u062f\u0631 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u061f \u0628\u0627\u0632 \u0622\u0646 \u062c\u0646\u0627\u0628 \u062a\u0648\u06cc\u06cc\u062a \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u06a9\u0647 \u0645\u0627\u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u0631\u0627 \u0627\u0632 \u0686\u0634\u0645 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0628\u06cc\u0646\u06cc\u0645. \u0634\u0645\u0627 \u063a\u0644\u0637 \u0645\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u06cc\u062f! \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u06af\u0631\u0628\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0647\u062f\u0628\u0627\u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0632\u0647 \u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0635\u0631\u06cc\u062d \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0631\u0627 \u0645\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u062f.\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0645\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0639 \u0648 \u0639\u0632\u062a \u0645\u0644\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u067e\u0627\u06cc\u0628\u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0645 \u0648\u0647\u0631\u06a9\u0633 \u0622\u0646 \u0631\u0627 \u062a\u0647\u062f\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0646\u062f \u0628\u062f\u0648\u0646 \u0647\u06cc\u0686 \u0645\u0644\u0627\u062d\u0638\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc \u0628\u0627\u0627\u0648 \u0631\u0648\u0628\u0631\u0648 \u0645\u06cc\u0634\u0648\u06cc\u0645 \u0648\u0636\u0631\u0628\u0647 \u0645\u06cc\u0632\u0646\u06cc\u0645.|last=\u0641\u0627\u0631\u0633\u06cc|first=KHAMENEI IR {{!}}|date=2020-01-01|website=@Khamenei_fa|language=fa|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Bahrain}} - Bahrain's Foreign Ministry released a statement supporting the airstrike.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bahrain expresses support for U.S. strikes on Kataib Hizbollah facilities in Iraq, Syria: statement |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa-bahrain/bahrain-expresses-support-for-us-strikes-on-kataib-hizbollah-facilities-in-iraq-syria-statement-idUSKBN1YY003 |accessdate=30 December 2019 |work=Reuters |date=30 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Israel}} - Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] praised the airstrikes against the militia and emphasized the group's ties to Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Prime-Minister-Netanyahu-congratulates-Mike-Pompeo-on-US-attacks-in-Iraq-612564|title=Prime Minister Netanyahu congratulates Mike Pompeo on US attacks in Iraq|website=The Jerusalem Post &#124; JPost.com}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Russia}} - Russia\u2019s foreign ministry called the situation unacceptable and called for restraint from both sides.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog_entry/russia-denounces-us-airstrikes-hezbollah-attacks-in-iraq/|title=Russia denounces US airstrikes, Hezbollah attacks in Iraq|website=www.timesofisrael.com}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Hezbollah}} - In a statement, Lebanon's Hezbollah called the attack \"a blatant violation on the sovereignty, security and stability of Iraq and the Iraqi people\".<ref name=CNN2/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Iranian involvement in the Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[Iraqi protests (2019\u2013present)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 airstrikes]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis]]\n[[Category:American airstrikes during the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Attacks in Asia in 2019]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in Syria]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Operation Inherent Resolve]]\n", "name_user": "RopeTricks", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReactions in Iraq:fleshing out what this means", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/December_2019_United_States_airstrikes_in_Iraq_and_Syria"}
{"title_page": "Terry Riley", "text_new": "{{short description|American composer and performing musician}}\n{{Infobox musician\n| name                = Terry Riley\n| image               =Terry Riley.jpg\n| caption              = Riley in 2004\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Terrence Mitchell Riley\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1935|6|24}}\n| birth_place         = [[Colfax, California]], US\n| years_active = 1950s - present\n| instruments = [[Electric organ]], [[tape machine]], [[saxophone]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n| genre = [[Minimal music|Minimalism]], [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]], [[tape music]]\n| associated_acts = [[Kronos Quartet]], [[La Monte Young]], [[John Cale]], [[Pandit Pran Nath]], [[Stefano Scodanibbio]], [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], [[ARTE Quartett]]\n}}\n\n'''Terrence Mitchell Riley''' (born June 24, 1935) is an American composer and performing musician<ref name=\"Hooper\">{{cite journal|last=Hooper|first=Greg|date=June\u2013July 2006|title=Hear and now: Terry Riley in Australia|journal=RealTime|location=Australia|issue=73|page=33|url=http://www.realtimearts.net/article/73/8136}}</ref><ref name=\"Examiner\">{{cite web|url=http://www.examiner.com/article/terry-riley-s-benefit-performance-for-old-first-concerts|title=Terry Riley's benefit performance for Old First Concerts|date=2012-03-24|website=Examiner.com|accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> best known as a pioneer of the [[minimalist music|minimalist]] school of composition.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Influenced by [[jazz]] and [[Indian classical music]], his music became notable for its innovative use of repetition, [[tape music]] techniques, and [[delay (audio effect)|delay system]]s.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|last1=Ankeny|first1=Jason|title=Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/terry-riley-mn0000750519|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> \n\nRiley is best known for his 1964  composition ''[[In C]]'' and 1969 album ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'', both considered landmarks of minimalism and important influences on [[experimental music|experimental]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[electronic music]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Since the 1970s, he has collaborated extensively with [[chamber ensemble]] the [[Kronos Quartet]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n\n==Life==\nBorn in [[Colfax, California]] in 1935, Riley began performing as a solo pianist during the 1950s.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> During that decade, he studied composition at [[San Francisco State University]], the [[San Francisco Conservatory]], and [[University of California, Berkeley]], studying with [[Seymour Shifrin]] and [[Robert Erickson]]. He was involved in the experimental [[San Francisco Tape Music Center]], working with [[Morton Subotnick]], [[Steve Reich]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], and [[Ramon Sender]]. Throughout the 1960s he  also traveled frequently in Europe, taking in musical influences and supporting himself by playing in [[piano bar]]s.\n\nHis most influential teacher was [[Pandit Pran Nath]] (1918\u20131996), a master of Indian classical voice who also taught [[La Monte Young]], [[Marian Zazeela]], and [[Michael Harrison (musician)|Michael Harrison]]. Riley made numerous trips to India over the course of their association to study and accompany him on [[tabla]], [[Tanpura|tambura]], and voice. In 1971 he joined the [[Mills College]] faculty to teach Indian classical music. Riley also cites [[John Cage]] and \"the really great [[chamber music]] groups of [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]], [[Charles Mingus]], [[Bill Evans]], and [[Gil Evans]]\" as influences on his work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluefat.com/0912/Terry_Riley2.htm |title=Like a Rainbow in Curved Air: Terry Riley|website=Bluefat.com}}</ref> He was awarded an Honorary Doctorate Degree in Music at [[Chapman University]] in 2007.\n\nRiley began his long-lasting association with the [[Kronos Quartet]] when he met their founder [[David Harrington (musician)|David Harrington]] while at Mills. Over the course of his career, Riley composed 13 [[string quartet]]s for the ensemble, in addition to other works. He wrote his first orchestral piece, ''Jade Palace'', in 1991, and has continued to pursue that avenue, with several commissioned orchestral compositions following. He is also currently performing and teaching both as an Indian [[raga]] vocalist and as a solo pianist.\n\nRiley continues to perform live, and was part of the [[All Tomorrow's Parties (music festival)|All Tomorrow's Parties]] festival in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2011/05/10-best-moments-all-tomorrows-parties/|title=The 10 Best Moments Of All Tomorrow's Parties|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Terry Riley 85.jpg|thumb|Riley at the [[Great American Music Hall]], San Francisco, 1985]]\n\n==Techniques==\nRiley's music is usually based on improvising through a series of [[musical mode|modal]] figures of [[phasing|different lengths]]. Works such as ''[[In C]]'' (1964) and the ''Keyboard Studies'' demonstrate this technique. The first performance of ''In C'' was given by [[Steve Reich]], [[Jon Gibson (minimalist musician)|Jon Gibson]], [[Pauline Oliveros]] and [[Morton Subotnick]]. Its form was an innovation: The piece consists of 53 separate modules of roughly one measure apiece, each containing a different musical pattern but each, as the title implies, in the key of C.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Honigmann|first1=David|title=In C, Barbican, London \u2013 review|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8959b73a-2f30-11e3-ae87-00144feab7de.html#axzz38lf7q1Lq|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> One performer beats a steady pulse of ''C''s on the piano to keep tempo. The others, in any number and on any instrument, perform these musical modules following a few loose guidelines, with the different musical modules interlocking in various ways as time goes on.\n\nIn the 1950s Riley was already working with [[tape loop]]s, a technology still in its infancy at the time; he would later, with the help of a sound engineer, create what he called a \"time-lag accumulator\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Video Art|last=Meigh-Andrews|first=Chris|publisher=Berg (Oxford International Publishers)|year=2006|isbn=978-1-84520-219-4|location=New York, NY and Oxford, UK|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofvideoar0000meig/page/94 94\u201395]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofvideoar0000meig/page/94}}</ref> He has continued manipulating tapes to musical effect, in the studio and in live performances throughout his career. An early tape loop piece titled ''Music for the Gift'' (1963) featured the trumpet playing of [[Chet Baker]]. It was during Riley's time in Paris, while composing this piece, that he conceived of and created the time-lag accumulator technique.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has composed using [[just intonation]] as well as [[microtones]].<ref name=\"holmes\" >Holmes, Thomas B. ''Electronic and Experimental Music'', Taylor & Francis (2008) p. 132, 362 {{ISBN|978-0-415-95781-6}}</ref> In New York City in the mid-1960s he played with his longtime friend La Monte Young, as well as with [[John Cale]] and tabla player [[Angus MacLise]], who were founding members of [[The Velvet Underground]]. Riley is credited as inspiring Cale's keyboard part on [[Lou Reed]]'s composition \"[[All Tomorrow's Parties]]\", which was sung by German actress [[Nico]] and included on the album ''[[The Velvet Underground and Nico]]'', recorded in 1966.\n\nRiley's famous overdubbed electronic album ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'' (recorded 1968, released 1969) inspired many later developments in electronic music. These include [[Pete Townshend]]'s [[organ (music)|organ]] parts on [[The Who]]'s \"[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]\" and \"[[Baba O'Riley]]\", the latter named in tribute to Riley as well as to [[Meher Baba]].<ref>This album also produced the name of psychedelic band [[Curved Air]].\n{{cite AV media notes\n |title      = The Who: The Ultimate Collection\n |titlelink  = The Ultimate_Collection (The_Who_album)\n |others   = The Who\n |year       = 2002\n |chapter = \n |url        = \n |first      = \n |last       = \n |pages      = 12\n |publisher  = MCA Records\n}}</ref> Charles Hazlewood, in his BBC documentary on Minimalism (Part 1) suggests that the album 'Tubular Bells' by Mike Oldfield was also inspired by Riley's example.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hazlewood|first1=Charles|title=Tones, Drones and Arpeggios: The Magic of Minimalism|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b09tbh10/tones-drones-and-arpeggios-the-magic-of-minimalism-series-1-1-california|website=BBC Website|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nRiley's collaborators have included the [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], the [[ARTE Quartett]], and, as mentioned, the Kronos Quartet. His 1995 ''Lisbon Concert'' recording features him in a solo piano format, improvising on his own works. In the liner notes Riley cites [[Art Tatum]], [[Bud Powell]] and [[Bill Evans]] as his piano \"heroes\", illustrating the importance of jazz to his conceptions.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has three children: one daughter, Colleen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://larecord.com/interviews/2009/11/19/terry-riley-interview-droning-dark-darkness |title=Terry Riley: Droning Dark Darkness |publisher=[[L.A. Record]] |date=November 19, 2009|first=Dan|last=Collins}}</ref> and two sons, [[Gyan Riley|Gyan]], who is a guitarist, and Shahn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2009/05/12/104061137/terry-and-gyan-riley-together-in-c|title=Terry And Gyan Riley: Together IN C|website=Npr.org}}</ref> He was married to Ann Riley until her death in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-01-10/entertainment/ca-1353_1_minimalist-terry-riley|title=A Composer on the Edge : Minimalist Terry Riley, on a journey of spiritual and artistic discovery, is deeply moved by the concept of artist-as-madman|first=Howard|last=Hersh|date=10 January 1993|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*1963: ''Music for The Gift'' (Organ of Corti 1, 1963) \n*1964: ''[[In C]]'', Columbia MS7178\n*1965: ''Reed Streams'', Mass Art Inc. M-131 \n*1967: ''You're No Good'', recorded in 1967 but unreleased until 2000<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Neal|first1=Sean|title=Terry Riley turns an R&B ditty into 20 minutes of madness|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/terry-riley-turns-rb-ditty-20-minutes-madness-223628|website=Avclub.com|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> (Cortical Foundation / Organ of Corti, 2000)<ref>{{cite web|title=Terry Riley Discography|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/terry-riley-mn0000750519/discography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*1968: ''Germ'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Germ-6-Terry-Riley-P-Mari%C3%A9tan-Keyboard-Study-2-Initiative-1--Syst%C3%A8mes/master/146863|title=Germ (6), Terry Riley, P. Mari\u00e9tan* - Keyboard Study 2 / Initiative 1 (+ Syst\u00e8mes)|website=Discogs}}</ref> with [[G\u00e9rard Fr\u00e9my]] & Martine Joste (Spalax CD 14542, 1998). Includes a [[Pierre Mari\u00e9tan]] track.\n*1969: ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'', CBS 64564\n*1971: ''[[Church of Anthrax]]'', with [[John Cale]] (CBS)\n*1972: ''Happy Ending'' (''Les Yeux Ferm\u00e9s'' film soundtrack), Warner Bros. Records France 46125; ''Les Yeux Ferm\u00e9s & Lifespan'', for solo electric organ; two soundtracks (2007 reissue)\n*1972: ''[[Persian Surgery Dervishes]]'', Shanti 83502\n*1975: ''Le Secret de la Vie'' (''Lifespan'' film soundtrack), Philips France 9120 037\n*1975: ''Descending Moonshine Dervishes'', Kuckuck Records\n*1978: ''[[Shri Camel]]'', CBS Masterworks M3519, for solo electronic organ tuned in just intonation and modified by digital delay<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shri-camel-mw0000897951|title=Shri Camel - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1983: ''Songs for the Ten Voices of the Two Prophets'', for two Prophet 5 synthesisers, Kuckuck Records\n*1984: ''[[Terry Riley: Cadenza on the Night Plain]]'', a collaboration with the [[Kronos Quartet]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-cadenza-on-the-night-plain-mw0000634232|title=Terry Riley: Cadenza on the Night Plain - Kronos Quartet, Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1984: ''[[Terry Riley and Krishna Bhatt: Terry Riley and Krishna Bhatt Duo]]'', a collaboration with [[Krishna Bhatt]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-Krishna-Bhatt-Terry-Riley-Krishna-Bhatt-Duo/release/9844086|title=Terry Riley, Krishna Bhatt - Terry Riley Krishna Bhatt Duo|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n*1985: ''No Man's Land''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-No-Mans-Land/release/1159313|title=Terry Riley - No Man's Land|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n*1986: ''The Harp of New Albion'', for piano tuned in [[just intonation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-harp-of-new-albion-mw0000086815|title=The Harp of New Albion - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1987: ''[[Chanting the Light of Foresight]]'', with [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]] in just intonation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-chanting-the-light-of-foresight-mw0001812715|title=Terry Riley: Chanting the Light of Foresight - Rova Saxophone Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1989: ''[[Salome Dances for Peace]]'', for the Kronos Quartet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/salome-dances-for-peace-mw0000680041|title=Salome Dances for Peace - Kronos Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1995: ''[[Lisbon Concert]]'', solo piano concert, recorded live July 16, 1995 Festival dos Capuchos, Teatro S\u00e3o Luis, Lisbon, Portugal., New Albion Records\n*1997: ''[[Lazy Afternoon Among the Crocodiles]]'', experimental album recorded with contrabassist [[Stefano Scodanibbio]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stefanoscodanibbio.com/discography/13.htm |title = Stefano Scodanibbio - Discography}}</ref>\n*1998: Piano Music of John Adams and Terry Riley, performed by [[Gloria Cheng]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/piano-music-of-john-adams-terry-riley-mw0001939606|title=Piano Music of John Adams & Terry Riley - Gloria Cheng &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2001: ''[[Moscow Conservatory]] Solo Piano Concert'', recording of a live performance on 18 April 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-Moscow-Conservatory-Solo-Piano-Concert/release/2933449|\ntitle=Terry Riley \u2013 Moscow Conservatory Solo Piano Concert (CD, Album) at Discogs}}</ref> \n*2002:  ''[[Sun Rings]]''  for the [[Kronos Quartet]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/composition/sun-rings-for-string-quartet-chorus-pre-recorded-spacescapes-mc0002508273|title=Sun Rings, for string quartet,\u2026 &#124; Details|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2002: ''Atlantis Nath'', hand-numbered signed edition of 1000 copies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/atlantis-nath-mw0000979895|title=Atlantis Nath - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2004: ''[[Terry Riley: The Cusp of Magic|The Cusp of Magic]]'', with the [[Kronos Quartet]], composed for his seventieth birthday, an ode to the rite of [[Midsummer]] Eve<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-cusp-of-magic-mw0000583160|title=The Cusp of Magic - Kronos Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2008: ''Banana Humberto'', piano concerto with [[Paul Dresher]] Ensemble<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/banana-humberto-mw0002109093|title=Banana Humberto - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2008: ''The Last Camel in Paris'', live solo electric organ performance in Paris, 1978<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-the-last-camel-in-paris-mw0001861476|title=Terry Riley: The Last Camel in Paris - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2010: ''Two Early Works'', the first-ever recordings of two of Riley's early compositions, performed by the Calder Quartet\n*2012: ''Aleph''\n*2015: ''G Song'', Kronos Quartet, in honor of his eightieth birthday\n*2019: ''The Lion's Throne'', with singer Amelia Cuni, recorded live (Sri Moonshine Music, SMM008)\n\n==Filmography==\n*1970 \u2013 ''Corridor''. Film by [[Standish Lawder]].\n*1975 \u2013 [[Lifespan (film)|''Lifespan'']]. Film by Alexander Whitelaw feat. Klaus Kinski, Tina Aumont and Hiram Keller. Soundtrack released as ''Le secret de la vie'' in France, on Philips LP 9120 037 (1975).\n*1976 \u2013 [[Crossroads (1976 film)|''Crossroads'']]. Film by [[Bruce Conner]].\n*1976 \u2013 ''Music With Roots in the Aether: Opera for Television''. Tape 6: Terry Riley. Produced and directed by [[Robert Ashley]]. New York, New York: Lovely Music.\n*1986 \u2013 ''In Between the Notes...a Portrait of Pandit Pran Nath, Master Indian Musician''. Produced by [[Other Minds (organization)|Other Minds]], directed by [[William Farley (director)|William Farley]].\n*1995 \u2013 ''Musical Outsiders: An American Legacy \u2013 Harry Partch, Lou Harrison, and Terry Riley''. Directed by Michael Blackwood.\n*2008 \u2013 \"A Rainbow In Curved Air\" features in the in-game soundtrack of ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]''. It can be found when listening to the fictional radio station, \"The Journey\".\n*2017 \u2013 ''[[Hochelaga, Land of Souls]]''. Film by Fran\u00e7ois Girard.\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Robert Carl|Carl, Robert]]. 2009. ''Terry Riley's in C''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-532528-7}}\n*[Anonymous] (2002). Album notes for ''The Who: The Ultimate Collection by The Who'', 12. MCA Records.\n*Potter, Keith (2000). ''Four Musical Minimalists: La Monte Young, Terry Riley, Steve Reich, Philip Glass. Music in the Twentieth Century series. Cambridge, UK; New York, New York: Cambridge University Press.\n*Edward Strickland, \"Terry Riley\". [[New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|Grove Music]] Online [http://www.grovemusic.com (subscription access)].\n*Meigh-Andrews, Chris, 2006. ''A History of Video Art.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://terryriley.net Official home page]\n*[http://www.innerviews.org/inner/riley.html 2014 in-depth interview on Innerviews]\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3049}}\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n*{{IMSLP|id=Riley%2C_Terry|cname=Terry Riley|license=cc}}\n* {{IMDb name|727178}}\n*[http://www.ubu.com/sound/riley.html Terry Riley page on Ubu Web] (audio and video)\n*Davidson, Robert. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20061214173648/http://www.topologymusic.com/index.php/short-biography-of-terry-riley/ Short Biography of Terry Riley].\" 1999.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070327164939/http://www.elisionfields.com/TerryRiley/ Elision Fields], Riley's management and CD label\n*[http://radiom.org/detail.php?omid=MC.1985.06.24.A A Concert in Honor of Terry Riley on his 50th Birthday], featuring the Kronos Quartet .\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040406002533/http://www.epitonic.com/artists/terryriley.html Epitonic.com: Terry Riley] featuring tracks from ''The Book of Abbeyozzud'' and ''The Light of Foresight'' (with [[Rova Saxophone Quartet|Rova]])\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050218215851/http://artofthestates.org/cgi-bin/composer.pl?comp=2 Art of the States: Terry Riley] ''In C'' (1964)\n*Golden, Barbara. \"Conversation with Terry Riley.\" [http://cec.concordia.ca/econtact/12_2/interviews_golden.html ''eContact! 12.2 \u2014 Interviews (2)''] (April 2010). Montr\u00e9al: [[Canadian Electroacoustic Community|CEC]].\n*Leopizzi, Marco. \"[http://www.musicaround.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50:-terry-riley-il-guru-del-minimalismo-intervista-&catid=40:interviste&Itemid=56 Terry Riley \u2014 Il guru del minimalismo].\" Interview from 1 June 2008. Musicaround.net. {{in lang|it}}\n*{{NewMusicBox|id=terry-riley-obsessed-and-passionate-about-all-music|title=Obsessed and Passionate About All Music|composer=Terry Riley|author=[[Frank J. Oteri]]|conducted=16 February 2001|published=1 June 2001}} (includes video)\n*[http://www.qaswa.com/thoughts/entry/terry_riley Interview with Terry Riley].\n*{{YouTube|5PNbEfLIEDs|Terry Riley \u2013 ''\"A Rainbow in Curved Air\"'' (18:47)}}\n\n<!---{{Terry Riley}} -- navbox to be created -->\n{{Minimal music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riley, Terry}}\n[[Category:American male classical composers]]\n[[Category:American classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Minimalist composers]]\n[[Category:Microtonal composers]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Postmodern composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Contemporary classical music performers]]\n[[Category:People from Placer County, California]]\n[[Category:BYG Actuel artists]]\n[[Category:Mills College faculty]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Robert Erickson]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Pran Nath (musician)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American composer and performing musician}}\n{{Infobox musician\n| name                = Terry Riley\n| image               =Terry Riley.jpg\n| caption              = Riley in 2004\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Terrence Mitchell Riley\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1935|6|24}}\n| birth_place         = [[Colfax, California]], US\n| years_active = 1950s - present\n| instruments = [[Electric organ]], [[tape machine]], [[saxophone]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n| genre = [[Minimal music|Minimalism]], [[avant-garde music|avant-garde]], [[tape music]]\n| associated_acts = [[Kronos Quartet]], [[La Monte Young]], [[John Cale]], [[Pandit Pran Nath]], [[Stefano Scodanibbio]], [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], [[ARTE Quartett]]\n}}\n\n'''Terrence Mitchell Riley''' (born June 24, 1935) is an American composer and performing musician<ref name=\"Hooper\">{{cite journal|last=Hooper|first=Greg|date=June\u2013July 2006|title=Hear and now: Terry Riley in Australia|journal=RealTime|location=Australia|issue=73|page=33|url=http://www.realtimearts.net/article/73/8136}}</ref><ref name=\"Examiner\">{{cite web|url=http://www.examiner.com/article/terry-riley-s-benefit-performance-for-old-first-concerts|title=Terry Riley's benefit performance for Old First Concerts|date=2012-03-24|website=Examiner.com|accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> best known as a pioneer of the [[minimalist music|minimalist]] school of composition.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Influenced by [[jazz]] and [[Indian classical music]], his music became notable for its innovative use of repetition, [[tape music]] techniques, and [[delay (audio effect)|delay system]]s.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|last1=Ankeny|first1=Jason|title=Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/terry-riley-mn0000750519|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> \n\nRiley is best known for his 1964  composition ''[[In C]]'' and 1969 album ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'', both considered landmarks of minimalism and important influences on [[experimental music|experimental]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[electronic music]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Since the 1970s, he has collaborated extensively with [[chamber ensemble]] the [[Kronos Quartet]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n\n==Life==\nBorn in [[Colfax, California]] in 1935, Riley began performing as a solo pianist during the 1950s.<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> During that decade, he studied composition at [[San Francisco State University]], the [[San Francisco Conservatory]], and [[University of California, Berkeley]], studying with [[Seymour Shifrin]] and [[Robert Erickson]]. He was involved in the experimental [[San Francisco Tape Music Center]], working with [[Morton Subotnick]], [[Steve Reich]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], and [[Ramon Sender]]. Throughout the 1960s he  also traveled frequently in Europe, taking in musical influences and supporting himself by playing in [[piano bar]]s.\n\nHis most influential teacher was [[Pandit Pran Nath]] (1918\u20131996), a master of Indian classical voice who also taught [[La Monte Young]], [[Marian Zazeela]], and [[Michael Harrison (musician)|Michael Harrison]]. Riley made numerous trips to India over the course of their association to study and accompany him on [[tabla]], [[Tanpura|tambura]], and voice. In 1971 he joined the [[Mills College]] faculty to teach Indian classical music. Riley also cites [[John Cage]] and \"the really great [[chamber music]] groups of [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]], [[Charles Mingus]], [[Bill Evans]], and [[Gil Evans]]\" as influences on his work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluefat.com/0912/Terry_Riley2.htm |title=Like a Rainbow in Curved Air: Terry Riley|website=Bluefat.com}}</ref>He was awarded an Honorary Doctorate Degree in Music at [[Chapman University]] in 2007.\n\nRiley began his long-lasting association with the [[Kronos Quartet]] when he met their founder [[David Harrington (musician)|David Harrington]] while at Mills. Over the course of his career, Riley composed 13 [[string quartet]]s for the ensemble, in addition to other works. He wrote his first orchestral piece, ''Jade Palace'', in 1991, and has continued to pursue that avenue, with several commissioned orchestral compositions following. He is also currently performing and teaching both as an Indian [[raga]] vocalist and as a solo pianist.\n\nRiley continues to perform live, and was part of the [[All Tomorrow's Parties (music festival)|All Tomorrow's Parties]] festival in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2011/05/10-best-moments-all-tomorrows-parties/|title=The 10 Best Moments Of All Tomorrow's Parties|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Terry Riley 85.jpg|thumb|Riley at the [[Great American Music Hall]], San Francisco, 1985]]\n\n==Techniques==\nRiley's music is usually based on improvising through a series of [[musical mode|modal]] figures of [[phasing|different lengths]]. Works such as ''[[In C]]'' (1964) and the ''Keyboard Studies'' demonstrate this technique. The first performance of ''In C'' was given by [[Steve Reich]], [[Jon Gibson (minimalist musician)|Jon Gibson]], [[Pauline Oliveros]] and [[Morton Subotnick]]. Its form was an innovation: The piece consists of 53 separate modules of roughly one measure apiece, each containing a different musical pattern but each, as the title implies, in the key of C.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Honigmann|first1=David|title=In C, Barbican, London \u2013 review|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8959b73a-2f30-11e3-ae87-00144feab7de.html#axzz38lf7q1Lq|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> One performer beats a steady pulse of ''C''s on the piano to keep tempo. The others, in any number and on any instrument, perform these musical modules following a few loose guidelines, with the different musical modules interlocking in various ways as time goes on.\n\nIn the 1950s Riley was already working with [[tape loop]]s, a technology still in its infancy at the time; he would later, with the help of a sound engineer, create what he called a \"time-lag accumulator\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Video Art|last=Meigh-Andrews|first=Chris|publisher=Berg (Oxford International Publishers)|year=2006|isbn=978-1-84520-219-4|location=New York, NY and Oxford, UK|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofvideoar0000meig/page/94 94\u201395]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofvideoar0000meig/page/94}}</ref> He has continued manipulating tapes to musical effect, in the studio and in live performances throughout his career. An early tape loop piece titled ''Music for the Gift'' (1963) featured the trumpet playing of [[Chet Baker]]. It was during Riley's time in Paris, while composing this piece, that he conceived of and created the time-lag accumulator technique.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has composed using [[just intonation]] as well as [[microtones]].<ref name=\"holmes\" >Holmes, Thomas B. ''Electronic and Experimental Music'', Taylor & Francis (2008) p. 132, 362 {{ISBN|978-0-415-95781-6}}</ref> In New York City in the mid-1960s he played with his longtime friend La Monte Young, as well as with [[John Cale]] and tabla player [[Angus MacLise]], who were founding members of [[The Velvet Underground]]. Riley is credited as inspiring Cale's keyboard part on [[Lou Reed]]'s composition \"[[All Tomorrow's Parties]]\", which was sung by German actress [[Nico]] and included on the album ''[[The Velvet Underground and Nico]]'', recorded in 1966.\n\nRiley's famous overdubbed electronic album ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'' (recorded 1968, released 1969) inspired many later developments in electronic music. These include [[Pete Townshend]]'s [[organ (music)|organ]] parts on [[The Who]]'s \"[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]\" and \"[[Baba O'Riley]]\", the latter named in tribute to Riley as well as to [[Meher Baba]].<ref>This album also produced the name of psychedelic band [[Curved Air]].\n{{cite AV media notes\n |title      = The Who: The Ultimate Collection\n |titlelink  = The Ultimate_Collection (The_Who_album)\n |others   = The Who\n |year       = 2002\n |chapter = \n |url        = \n |first      = \n |last       = \n |pages      = 12\n |publisher  = MCA Records\n}}</ref> Charles Hazlewood, in his BBC documentary on Minimalism (Part 1) suggests that the album 'Tubular Bells' by Mike Oldfield was also inspired by Riley's example.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hazlewood|first1=Charles|title=Tones, Drones and Arpeggios: The Magic of Minimalism|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b09tbh10/tones-drones-and-arpeggios-the-magic-of-minimalism-series-1-1-california|website=BBC Website|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nRiley's collaborators have included the [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]], [[Pauline Oliveros]], the [[ARTE Quartett]], and, as mentioned, the Kronos Quartet. His 1995 ''Lisbon Concert'' recording features him in a solo piano format, improvising on his own works. In the liner notes Riley cites [[Art Tatum]], [[Bud Powell]] and [[Bill Evans]] as his piano \"heroes\", illustrating the importance of jazz to his conceptions.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has three children: one daughter, Colleen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://larecord.com/interviews/2009/11/19/terry-riley-interview-droning-dark-darkness |title=Terry Riley: Droning Dark Darkness |publisher=[[L.A. Record]] |date=November 19, 2009|first=Dan|last=Collins}}</ref> and two sons, [[Gyan Riley|Gyan]], who is a guitarist, and Shahn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2009/05/12/104061137/terry-and-gyan-riley-together-in-c|title=Terry And Gyan Riley: Together IN C|website=Npr.org}}</ref> He was married to Ann Riley until her death in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-01-10/entertainment/ca-1353_1_minimalist-terry-riley|title=A Composer on the Edge : Minimalist Terry Riley, on a journey of spiritual and artistic discovery, is deeply moved by the concept of artist-as-madman|first=Howard|last=Hersh|date=10 January 1993|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*1963: ''Music for The Gift'' (Organ of Corti 1, 1963) \n*1964: ''[[In C]]'', Columbia MS7178\n*1965: ''Reed Streams'', Mass Art Inc. M-131 \n*1967: ''You're No Good'', recorded in 1967 but unreleased until 2000<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Neal|first1=Sean|title=Terry Riley turns an R&B ditty into 20 minutes of madness|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/terry-riley-turns-rb-ditty-20-minutes-madness-223628|website=Avclub.com|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> (Cortical Foundation / Organ of Corti, 2000)<ref>{{cite web|title=Terry Riley Discography|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/terry-riley-mn0000750519/discography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*1968: ''Germ'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Germ-6-Terry-Riley-P-Mari%C3%A9tan-Keyboard-Study-2-Initiative-1--Syst%C3%A8mes/master/146863|title=Germ (6), Terry Riley, P. Mari\u00e9tan* - Keyboard Study 2 / Initiative 1 (+ Syst\u00e8mes)|website=Discogs}}</ref> with [[G\u00e9rard Fr\u00e9my]] & Martine Joste (Spalax CD 14542, 1998). Includes a [[Pierre Mari\u00e9tan]] track.\n*1969: ''[[A Rainbow in Curved Air]]'', CBS 64564\n*1971: ''[[Church of Anthrax]]'', with [[John Cale]] (CBS)\n*1972: ''Happy Ending'' (''Les Yeux Ferm\u00e9s'' film soundtrack), Warner Bros. Records France 46125; ''Les Yeux Ferm\u00e9s & Lifespan'', for solo electric organ; two soundtracks (2007 reissue)\n*1972: ''[[Persian Surgery Dervishes]]'', Shanti 83502\n*1975: ''Le Secret de la Vie'' (''Lifespan'' film soundtrack), Philips France 9120 037\n*1975: ''Descending Moonshine Dervishes'', Kuckuck Records\n*1978: ''[[Shri Camel]]'', CBS Masterworks M3519, for solo electronic organ tuned in just intonation and modified by digital delay<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shri-camel-mw0000897951|title=Shri Camel - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1983: ''Songs for the Ten Voices of the Two Prophets'', for two Prophet 5 synthesisers, Kuckuck Records\n*1984: ''[[Terry Riley: Cadenza on the Night Plain]]'', a collaboration with the [[Kronos Quartet]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-cadenza-on-the-night-plain-mw0000634232|title=Terry Riley: Cadenza on the Night Plain - Kronos Quartet, Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1984: ''[[Terry Riley and Krishna Bhatt: Terry Riley and Krishna Bhatt Duo]]'', a collaboration with [[Krishna Bhatt]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-Krishna-Bhatt-Terry-Riley-Krishna-Bhatt-Duo/release/9844086|title=Terry Riley, Krishna Bhatt - Terry Riley Krishna Bhatt Duo|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n*1985: ''No Man's Land''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-No-Mans-Land/release/1159313|title=Terry Riley - No Man's Land|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n*1986: ''The Harp of New Albion'', for piano tuned in [[just intonation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-harp-of-new-albion-mw0000086815|title=The Harp of New Albion - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1987: ''[[Chanting the Light of Foresight]]'', with [[Rova Saxophone Quartet]] in just intonation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-chanting-the-light-of-foresight-mw0001812715|title=Terry Riley: Chanting the Light of Foresight - Rova Saxophone Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1989: ''[[Salome Dances for Peace]]'', for the Kronos Quartet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/salome-dances-for-peace-mw0000680041|title=Salome Dances for Peace - Kronos Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*1995: ''[[Lisbon Concert]]'', solo piano concert, recorded live July 16, 1995 Festival dos Capuchos, Teatro S\u00e3o Luis, Lisbon, Portugal., New Albion Records\n*1997: ''[[Lazy Afternoon Among the Crocodiles]]'', experimental album recorded with contrabassist [[Stefano Scodanibbio]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stefanoscodanibbio.com/discography/13.htm |title = Stefano Scodanibbio - Discography}}</ref>\n*1998: Piano Music of John Adams and Terry Riley, performed by [[Gloria Cheng]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/piano-music-of-john-adams-terry-riley-mw0001939606|title=Piano Music of John Adams & Terry Riley - Gloria Cheng &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2001: ''[[Moscow Conservatory]] Solo Piano Concert'', recording of a live performance on 18 April 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Terry-Riley-Moscow-Conservatory-Solo-Piano-Concert/release/2933449|\ntitle=Terry Riley \u2013 Moscow Conservatory Solo Piano Concert (CD, Album) at Discogs}}</ref> \n*2002:  ''[[Sun Rings]]''  for the [[Kronos Quartet]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/composition/sun-rings-for-string-quartet-chorus-pre-recorded-spacescapes-mc0002508273|title=Sun Rings, for string quartet,\u2026 &#124; Details|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2002: ''Atlantis Nath'', hand-numbered signed edition of 1000 copies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/atlantis-nath-mw0000979895|title=Atlantis Nath - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2004: ''[[Terry Riley: The Cusp of Magic|The Cusp of Magic]]'', with the [[Kronos Quartet]], composed for his seventieth birthday, an ode to the rite of [[Midsummer]] Eve<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-cusp-of-magic-mw0000583160|title=The Cusp of Magic - Kronos Quartet &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2008: ''Banana Humberto'', piano concerto with [[Paul Dresher]] Ensemble<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/banana-humberto-mw0002109093|title=Banana Humberto - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2008: ''The Last Camel in Paris'', live solo electric organ performance in Paris, 1978<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/terry-riley-the-last-camel-in-paris-mw0001861476|title=Terry Riley: The Last Camel in Paris - Terry Riley &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n*2010: ''Two Early Works'', the first-ever recordings of two of Riley's early compositions, performed by the Calder Quartet\n*2012: ''Aleph''\n*2015: ''G Song'', Kronos Quartet, in honor of his eightieth birthday\n*2019: ''The Lion's Throne'', with singer Amelia Cuni, recorded live (Sri Moonshine Music, SMM008)\n\n==Filmography==\n*1970 \u2013 ''Corridor''. Film by [[Standish Lawder]].\n*1975 \u2013 [[Lifespan (film)|''Lifespan'']]. Film by Alexander Whitelaw feat. Klaus Kinski, Tina Aumont and Hiram Keller. Soundtrack released as ''Le secret de la vie'' in France, on Philips LP 9120 037 (1975).\n*1976 \u2013 [[Crossroads (1976 film)|''Crossroads'']]. Film by [[Bruce Conner]].\n*1976 \u2013 ''Music With Roots in the Aether: Opera for Television''. Tape 6: Terry Riley. Produced and directed by [[Robert Ashley]]. New York, New York: Lovely Music.\n*1986 \u2013 ''In Between the Notes...a Portrait of Pandit Pran Nath, Master Indian Musician''. Produced by [[Other Minds (organization)|Other Minds]], directed by [[William Farley (director)|William Farley]].\n*1995 \u2013 ''Musical Outsiders: An American Legacy \u2013 Harry Partch, Lou Harrison, and Terry Riley''. Directed by Michael Blackwood.\n*2008 \u2013 \"A Rainbow In Curved Air\" features in the in-game soundtrack of ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]''. It can be found when listening to the fictional radio station, \"The Journey\".\n*2017 \u2013 ''[[Hochelaga, Land of Souls]]''. Film by Fran\u00e7ois Girard.\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Robert Carl|Carl, Robert]]. 2009. ''Terry Riley's in C''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-532528-7}}\n*[Anonymous] (2002). Album notes for ''The Who: The Ultimate Collection by The Who'', 12. MCA Records.\n*Potter, Keith (2000). ''Four Musical Minimalists: La Monte Young, Terry Riley, Steve Reich, Philip Glass. Music in the Twentieth Century series. Cambridge, UK; New York, New York: Cambridge University Press.\n*Edward Strickland, \"Terry Riley\". [[New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|Grove Music]] Online [http://www.grovemusic.com (subscription access)].\n*Meigh-Andrews, Chris, 2006. ''A History of Video Art.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://terryriley.net Official home page]\n*[http://www.innerviews.org/inner/riley.html 2014 in-depth interview on Innerviews]\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3049}}\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n*{{IMSLP|id=Riley%2C_Terry|cname=Terry Riley|license=cc}}\n* {{IMDb name|727178}}\n*[http://www.ubu.com/sound/riley.html Terry Riley page on Ubu Web] (audio and video)\n*Davidson, Robert. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20061214173648/http://www.topologymusic.com/index.php/short-biography-of-terry-riley/ Short Biography of Terry Riley].\" 1999.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070327164939/http://www.elisionfields.com/TerryRiley/ Elision Fields], Riley's management and CD label\n*[http://radiom.org/detail.php?omid=MC.1985.06.24.A A Concert in Honor of Terry Riley on his 50th Birthday], featuring the Kronos Quartet .\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040406002533/http://www.epitonic.com/artists/terryriley.html Epitonic.com: Terry Riley] featuring tracks from ''The Book of Abbeyozzud'' and ''The Light of Foresight'' (with [[Rova Saxophone Quartet|Rova]])\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050218215851/http://artofthestates.org/cgi-bin/composer.pl?comp=2 Art of the States: Terry Riley] ''In C'' (1964)\n*Golden, Barbara. \"Conversation with Terry Riley.\" [http://cec.concordia.ca/econtact/12_2/interviews_golden.html ''eContact! 12.2 \u2014 Interviews (2)''] (April 2010). Montr\u00e9al: [[Canadian Electroacoustic Community|CEC]].\n*Leopizzi, Marco. \"[http://www.musicaround.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50:-terry-riley-il-guru-del-minimalismo-intervista-&catid=40:interviste&Itemid=56 Terry Riley \u2014 Il guru del minimalismo].\" Interview from 1 June 2008. Musicaround.net. {{in lang|it}}\n*{{NewMusicBox|id=terry-riley-obsessed-and-passionate-about-all-music|title=Obsessed and Passionate About All Music|composer=Terry Riley|author=[[Frank J. Oteri]]|conducted=16 February 2001|published=1 June 2001}} (includes video)\n*[http://www.qaswa.com/thoughts/entry/terry_riley Interview with Terry Riley].\n*{{Y